{
  "question": "This line chart displays average satisfaction score (1–10) by department. Which of the following statements is most accurate?",
  "options": {
    "A": "There is a cyclical pattern that repeats every two categories along the x‑axis.",
    "B": "The average across all categories is identical, since the line starts and ends at similar levels.",
    "C": "Finance has the highest score among all categories shown.",
    "D": "The chart shows a smooth and predictable progression in the metric as you move from the first to the last category."
  },
  "correctAnswer": "C",
  "wrongDueToMisleaderAnswer": "D",
  "misleader": "continous_encoding_for_categorical_data",
  "chartType": "line_chart",
  "task": "Find Correlations/Trends",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "ifLabelled": "False",
  "explanation": "This line chart uses a continuous line over department that are purely categorical (e.g., HR, Engineering, Operations, ...). Connecting points suggests there is a meaningful smooth progression from left to right, which is conceptually incorrect — these categories have no inherent numeric order. The y‑axis values are on a 1 to 10 scale, but any comparison across categories should be made with a discrete chart such as a bar chart, not by reading trends from the connecting line."
